<tbody>
<tr>
<td>License compliance</td>
<td>✅</td>
<td>Non-blocking license compliance alerts become blockers in PRs even though the license compliance-specific rule merge blocking rule was not enabled. This creates high friction for license compliance (LC) because LC alerts cannot be easily dismissed and require a review process. This means the legacy rule can significantly increase the workflow of LC reviewers that they did not anticipate.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Copilot Code Review</td>
<td>Exemption granted</td>
<td>CCR comments were specifically given an exemption from this rule, I guess because it was causing a lot of problems for customers. I haven't followed every thread, but there's a <a href="https://github.slack.com/archives/C04M8NHLUTZ/p1769800074483529" rel="nofollow">Slack discussion</a> confirming this exemption.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Code quality</td>
<td>Requires testing</td>
<td>This still needs testing / confirmation. This basically means code quality findings in PRs will be blocking even thought the CQ-specifc rule wasn't configured to be blocking. Not sure if this will be that big of a deal because I think CQ findings can be dismissed directly anyways. Will need CQ team weigh in.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Code scanning</td>
<td>Requires testing</td>
<td>I don't think they've migrated to the ARC component from the Developer Friendly Alert (DFA) yet but last I heard they plan to soon. I'm not sure if DFAs were affected because they might not have counted as "comments" in the past but will need testing to confirm. If Code scanning (CS) is affected, then for repos with CS delegated dismissals enabled, the workflow to resolve a comment can be increased by this non-CS-specific rule, similar to license compliance.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></markdown-accessiblity-table>
<p dir="auto">I've started a conversation in the <code class="notranslate">#comment-design</code> channel and we've discussed potentially introducing a sub-setting where admins can decide if the existing rule should include system comments from GitHub features or not. This is just a first draft idea so really additional input from other folks that may be affected would be valuable.</p>
